#### Subgroups

The notion of [Eastern Algonquian](/Eastern_Algonquian_languages) as a distinct genetic subgroup is widely accepted. Conversely, the [Plains](/Plains_Algonquian_languages) and [Central](/Central_Algonquian_languages) groupings are not considered genetic units. Instead, they represent [areal](/Areal_feature) groupings, where shared linguistic traits are more a product of prolonged [language contact](/Language_contact) and geographical proximity than of a direct common ancestor.

Paul Proulx, however, has presented a dissenting view, arguing that the traditional classification is flawed. He posits that Central Algonquian, which he includes the Plains Algonquian languages within, *is* a genetic subgroup. Under his model, [Eastern Algonquian](/Eastern_Algonquian_languages) would then be composed of several divergent subgroups. This alternative classification, however, has not garnered widespread acceptance among specialists in the field.

The prevailing and commonly accepted scheme for subgrouping is that proposed by [Ives Goddard](/Ives_Goddard) in 1994. His model suggests that [Proto-Algonquian](/Proto-Algonquian_language) originated with populations located to the west, who subsequently migrated eastward. While Goddard didn't pinpoint a specific western [urheimat](/Linguistic_homeland) in his 1994 paper, his reconstruction aligns well with the linguistic evidence. According to this model, the [Blackfoot](/Blackfoot_language) language branched off first, which is consistent with its status as the most linguistically divergent of the Algonquian languages. Following this initial split, in a general west-to-east progression, the subsequent branchings occurred:

*   First, the [Arapaho–Gros Ventre](/Arapahoan_languages), [Cree–Montagnais](/Cree_language), [Menominee](/Menominee_language), and [Cheyenne](/Cheyenne_language) languages diverged.
*   Next came the core Great Lakes languages: [Ojibwe–Potawatomi](/Ojibwe_language), [Shawnee](/Shawnee_language), [Sauk–Fox–Kickapoo](/Fox_language), and [Miami–Illinois](/Miami%E2%80%93Illinois_language).
*   Finally, the [Proto-Eastern Algonquian](/Eastern_Algonquian_languages) lineage emerged.

This reconstruction of historical development aligns remarkably well with the observed degrees of linguistic divergence within the family. Languages that branched off earlier, typically in the west, exhibit greater divergence, while those that branched off later, particularly in the east, show shallower subgroupings, such as [Eastern Algonquian](/Eastern_Algonquian_languages) and what might be considered "Core Central" languages. This general west-to-east pattern is supported by J.P. Denny's (1991) hypothesis that the speakers of [Proto-Algonquian](/Proto-Algonquian_language) might have migrated eastward from the [Plateau](/Columbia_Plateau) region of [Idaho](/Idaho) and [Oregon](/Oregon), or from the [Rocky Mountain-Great Plains](/Continental_Divide_of_the_Americas) boundary area in [Montana](/Montana). As they moved, various subgroups would have separated and settled. Goddard also highlights documented evidence of historical [language contact](/Language_contact) between [Eastern Algonquian](/Eastern_Algonquian_languages) and [Cree–Montagnais](/Cree_language), as well as between [Cheyenne](/Cheyenne_language) and [Arapaho–Gros Ventre](/Arapahoan_languages). The influence between [Cree](/Cree_language) and [Ojibwe](/Ojibwe_language) has been particularly extensive and sustained over time.

There's a suggestion that the "Eastern Great Lakes" languages – which Goddard refers to as "Core Central," encompassing [Ojibwe–Potawatomi](/Ojibwe_language), [Shawnee](/Shawnee_language), [Sauk–Fox–Kickapoo](/Fox_language), and [Miami–Illinois](/Miami%E2%80%93Illinois_language), but excluding [Cree–Montagnais](/Cree_language) and [Menominee](/Menominee_language) – might also form their own distinct genetic grouping within Algonquian. These languages share some notable lexical and phonological innovations, though this theory is still under development and considered speculative.

The extinct [Beothuk language](/Beothuk_language) of [Newfoundland](/Newfoundland_and_Labrador) has also been tentatively linked to the Algonquian family. Its speakers were geographically close to Algonquian-speaking peoples, and shared genetic markers with the [Miꞌkmaq](/Mi%EA%9E%8Ckmaq_people), who are Algonquian speakers. However, the available linguistic evidence is sparse and poorly documented, making a definitive connection unlikely.

#### Grammatical Features

The Algonquian languages are recognized for their intricate [polysynthetic](/Polysynthetic_language) [morphology](/Morphology_(linguistics)) and a highly developed [verb](/Verb) system. This complexity means that statements requiring multiple words in [English](/English_language) can often be condensed into a single word. For instance, in [Menominee](/Menominee_language), the word *paehtāwāēwesew* translates to 'He is heard by higher powers', constructed from elements meaning 'hear', 'spirit', a passive marker, and a third-person subject. Similarly, in [Plains Cree](/Plains_Cree_language), *kāstāhikoyahk* means 'it frightens us'. These languages have been subjects of extensive study by scholars such as [Leonard Bloomfield](/Leonard_Bloomfield) and [Ives Goddard](/Ives_Goddard).

A fundamental characteristic of Algonquian nouns is the distinction between [animate](/Animacy) and inanimate categories. All nouns are classified as either animate or inanimate. The semantic basis for this classification remains a topic of ongoing debate. Some scholars argue for a clear semantic distinction, while others view it as primarily a [syntactic](/Syntax) feature. Linguists who lean towards a structuralist perspective argue that the lack of a consistent semantic system for animacy classification points to it being a purely linguistic construct. Conversely, anthropological linguists emphasize the deep connection between animacy and concepts of spiritual significance.

Another critical distinction is between nouns marked as proximate and those marked as [obviative](/Obviative). Proximate nouns are considered the most central or important elements within a discourse, whereas obviative nouns are those deemed less central.

Pronouns in these languages are complex, distinguishing between three persons, two numbers (singular and plural), [inclusive and exclusive first person plural](/Inclusive_and_exclusive_we), and also featuring proximate and obviative third persons. Verbs are typically classified into four main categories: [transitive](/Transitive_verb) verbs with an animate object (TA), transitive verbs with an inanimate object (TI), [intransitive](/Intransitive_verb) verbs with an animate subject (AI), and intransitive verbs with an inanimate subject (II).

A particularly notable feature of the Algonquian languages is their [direct–inverse](/Direct%E2%80%93inverse_alignment) or hierarchical [morphosyntactic alignment](/Morphosyntactic_alignment). This system distinguishes between an unmarked voice, where the subject holds a higher rank than the object according to a person hierarchy, and a marked voice, where the reverse relationship applies.

