##### Loanwords

Due to the early contact between Europeans and Algonquian-speaking peoples in [North America](/North_America), the language family has contributed numerous words to the [English](/English_language) lexicon. The names of many [U.S. states](/U.S._states) in the eastern and midwestern regions, such as [Massachusetts](/Massachusetts), [Connecticut](/Connecticut), [Illinois](/Illinois), [Michigan](/Michigan), and [Wisconsin](/Wisconsin), are of Algonquian origin. Likewise, numerous cities bear names derived from these languages, including [Milwaukee](/Milwaukee) and [Chicago](/Chicago). Even [Ottawa](/Ottawa), the capital of [Canada](/Canada), is named after the [Odawa people](/Odawa_people), an Algonquian nation.

For a more comprehensive exploration of geographical names derived from three Algonquian languages, one can refer to the external link to J. Hammond Trumbull's work.

